The paper analyzes readership statistics recorded in social reference management systems to create knowledge domain visualizations, which involves data analysis and visualization techniques. This makes it likely to belong to the Digital Libraries (cs.DL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on educational technology research, which involves the use of technology in education, making it relevant to the Cybernetics (cs.CY) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. The paper also discusses biases introduced by the characteristics of the readers, which is relevant to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses co-readership patterns to map the field of educational technology, which involves information retrieval techniques, making it relevant to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
